===[[National Basketball Association]]=== * October 25, 2016 – April 12, 2017: [[2016–17 NBA season]] ** Top Seed: {{flagicon|California}} [[2016–17 Golden State Warriors season|Golden State Warriors]] ** [[List of National Basketball Association annual scoring leaders|Top Scorer]]: {{flagicon|California}} [[Russell Westbrook]] ({{flagicon|Oklahoma}} [[2016–17 Oklahoma City Thunder season|Oklahoma City Thunder]]) * February 19: [[2017 NBA All-Star Game]] at the [[Smoothie King Center]] in {{flagicon|USA}} [[New Orleans]] ** The [[Western Conference (NBA)|West]] defeated the [[Eastern Conference (NBA)|East]], 192–182. ** [[NBA All-Star Game Most Valuable Player Award|MVP]]: {{flagicon|Illinois}} [[Anthony Davis (basketball)|Anthony Davis]] ({{flagicon|Louisiana}} [[2016–17 New Orleans Pelicans season|New Orleans Pelicans]]) ** [[NBA All-Star Celebrity Game]]: Team East defeated Team West, 88–59. ** [[Rising Stars Challenge]]: Team World defeated Team USA, 150–141. ** [[NBA All-Star Weekend Skills Challenge]] Winner: {{flagicon|LAT}} [[Kristaps Porziņģis]] ({{flagicon|New York}} [[2016–17 New York Knicks season|New York Knicks]]) ** [[Three-Point Contest]] Winner: {{flagicon|Indiana}} [[Eric Gordon]] ({{flagicon|Texas}} [[2016–17 Houston Rockets season|Houston Rockets]]) ** [[Slam Dunk Contest]] Winner: {{flagicon|Indiana}} [[Glenn Robinson III]] ({{flagicon|Indiana}} [[2016–17 Indiana Pacers season|Indiana Pacers]]) * April 15 – June 12: [[2017 NBA Playoffs]] ** The {{flagicon|California}} [[2016–17 Golden State Warriors season|Golden State Warriors]] defeated the {{flagicon|Ohio}} [[2016–17 Cleveland Cavaliers season|Cleveland Cavaliers]], 4–1 in games played, to win their fifth NBA title. ** [[Bill Russell NBA Finals Most Valuable Player Award|MVP]]: {{flagicon|District of Columbia}} [[Kevin Durant]] (Golden State Warriors) * June 22: [[2017 NBA draft]] ** [[List of first overall NBA draft picks|#1 pick]]: {{flagicon|Maryland}} [[Markelle Fultz]] (to the {{flagicon|Pennsylvania}} [[2017–18 Philadelphia 76ers season|Philadelphia 76ers]] from the {{flagicon|Washington}} [[Washington Huskies men's basketball|Washington Huskies]])
===[[Women's National Basketball Association]]=== * April 13: [[2017 WNBA draft]] in {{flagicon|New York}} [[New York City]] at the Samsung 837 ** Top pick: {{flagicon|California}} [[Kelsey Plum]] (to the {{flagicon|Texas}} [[2017 San Antonio Stars season|San Antonio Stars]] from the {{flagicon|Washington}} [[2016–17 Washington Huskies women's basketball team|Washington Huskies]]) * May 13 – September 3: [[2017 WNBA season]] ** [[Western Conference (WNBA)|Western Conference winners]]: {{flagicon|Minnesota}} [[2017 Minnesota Lynx season|Minnesota Lynx]] ** [[Eastern Conference (WNBA)|Eastern Conference winners]]: {{flagicon|New York}} New York Liberty * July 22: [[2017 WNBA All-Star Game]] in {{flagicon|Washington}} [[KeyArena|Seattle]] ** The [[Western Conference (WNBA)|Western Conference]] defeated the [[Eastern Conference (WNBA)|Eastern Conference]], 130–121. ** [[WNBA All-Star Game Most Valuable Player Award|MVP]]: {{flagicon|Missouri}} [[Maya Moore]] ({{flagicon|Minnesota}} [[2017 Minnesota Lynx season|Minnesota Lynx]]) ** Three-Point Shootout winner: {{flagicon|Illinois}} [[Allie Quigley]] ({{flagicon|Illinois}} [[2017 Chicago Sky season|Chicago Sky]]) * September 6 – October 4: [[2017 WNBA Finals]] ** The {{flagicon|Minnesota}} [[2017 Minnesota Lynx season|Minnesota Lynx]] defeated the {{flagicon|California}} [[2017 Los Angeles Sparks season|Los Angeles Sparks]], 3–2 in games played, to win their fourth WNBA title.
===[[National Collegiate Athletic Association]]=== * March 14 – April 3: [[2017 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament]] (Final Four at [[University of Phoenix Stadium]] in [[Glendale, Arizona|Glendale]]) ** The {{flagicon|North Carolina}} [[2016–17 North Carolina Tar Heels men's basketball team|North Carolina Tar Heels]] defeated the {{flagicon|Washington}} [[2016–17 Gonzaga Bulldogs men's basketball team|Gonzaga Bulldogs]], 71–65, to win their sixth NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament title. * March 17 – April 2: [[2017 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament]] (Final Four at [[American Airlines Center]] in [[Dallas]]) ** The {{flagicon|South Carolina}} [[2016–17 South Carolina Gamecocks women's basketball team|South Carolina Gamecocks]] defeated the {{flagicon|Mississippi}} [[2016–17 Mississippi State Bulldogs women's basketball team|Mississippi State Bulldogs]], 67–55, to win their first NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament title.
===Club seasons and championships=== * September 29, 2016 – April 13: [[2016–17 ABA League]] ** {{flagicon|SRB}} [[KK Crvena zvezda]] defeated {{flagicon|CRO}} [[KK Cedevita]], 3–0 in games played, to win their third consecutive ABA League title. * September 29, 2016 – April 24: [[2016–17 Alpe Adria Cup]] ** {{flagicon|SVK}} [[MBK Rieker Komárno]] defeated {{flagicon|SLO}} [[KK Domžale]], 160–139 on aggregate, to win their first Alpe Adria Cup title. * October 2, 2016 – June 13, 2017: [[2016–17 VTB United League]] ** {{flagicon|RUS}} [[PBC CSKA Moscow|CSKA Moscow]] defeated fellow Russian team, [[BC Khimki]], 3–0 in series played, to win their sixth consecutive and eighth overall VTB United League title. * October 5, 2016 – March 19: [[2016–17 WABA League]] ([[WABA League 2016–17 Final Four|Final Four]] in {{flagicon|MNE}} [[Podgorica]]) ** {{flagicon|SLO}} [[ŽKK Athlete Celje|Athlete Celje]] defeated {{flagicon|BUL}} [[WBC Beroe|Beroe]], 61–57, to win their second WABA League title. {{flagicon|MNE}} [[ŽKK Budućnost Podgorica|Budućnost Bemax]] took third place. * October 10, 2016 – April 20: [[2016–17 BIBL]] ** {{flagicon|BUL}} [[BC Beroe]] defeated {{flagicon|MKD}} [[KK Kumanovo]], 161–128 on aggregate, to win their first BIBL title. * October 12, 2016 – May 21: [[2016–17 EuroLeague]] ([[2017 EuroLeague Final Four|Final Four]] at [[Sinan Erdem Dome]] in {{flagicon|TUR}} [[Istanbul]]) ** {{flagicon|TUR}} [[Fenerbahçe Men's Basketball|Fenerbahçe]] defeated {{flagicon|GRE}} [[Olympiacos B.C.]], 80–64, to win their first EuroLeague title. ** {{flagicon|RUS}} [[PBC CSKA Moscow]] took third place. * October 12, 2016 – April 5: [[2016–17 EuroCup Basketball]] ** {{flagicon|ESP}} [[Baloncesto Málaga|Unicaja]] defeated {{flagicon|ESP}} [[Valencia BC|Valencia Basket]], 2–1, in the [[2017 EuroCup Finals|EuroCup Finals]] to win their first [[EuroCup Basketball|EuroCup]] title. * October 18, 2016 – April 26: [[2016–17 FIBA Europe Cup]] ([[2017 FIBA Europe Cup Finals|Final]] in {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Chalon-sur-Saône]] & [[Nanterre]]) ** {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Nanterre 92]] defeated fellow French team, [[Élan Chalon]], 140–137 on aggregate, to win their first FIBA Europe Cup title. * October 20, 2016 – April 30: [[2016–17 Basketball Champions League]] ([[2017 Basketball Champions League Final Four|Final Four]] at the [[Pabellón Insular Santiago Martín|Santiago Martín]] in {{flagicon|ESP}} [[San Cristóbal de La Laguna|La Laguna]]) (debut event) ** {{flagicon|ESP}} [[CB 1939 Canarias|Iberostar Tenerife]] defeated {{flagicon|TUR}} [[Banvit B.K.]], 63–59, to win the inaugural Basketball Champions League title. ** {{flagicon|FRA}} [[AS Monaco Basket|Monaco]] took third place. * November 25, 2016 – April 23: [[2016–17 ABL season]] ** {{flagicon|HKG}} [[Hong Kong Eastern Long Lions]] defeated {{flagicon|SIN}} [[Singapore Slingers]], 3–1 in the finals, to win their first ABL title. * January 20 – March 18: [[2017 FIBA Americas League]] in {{flagicon|MEX}} [[Mexicali]] and [[Monterrey]], {{flagicon|ARG}} [[Buenos Aires]], and {{flagicon|PUR}} [[Ponce, Puerto Rico|Ponce]] ** {{flagicon|VEN}} [[Guaros de Lara (basketball)|Guaros de Lara]] defeated {{flagicon|ARG}} [[Estudiantes de Bahía Blanca|Weber Bahía Basket]], 88–65, to win their second consecutive FIBA Americas League title. ** {{flagicon|PUR}} [[Leones de Ponce (basketball)|Leones de Ponce]] took third place. * September 24: [[2017 FIBA Intercontinental Cup]] in {{flagicon|ESP}} [[San Cristóbal de La Laguna|La Laguna]] ** {{flagicon|ESP}} [[CB 1939 Canarias|Iberostar Tenerife]] defeated {{flagicon|VEN}} [[Guaros de Lara (basketball)|Guaros de Lara]], 76–71, to win their first FIBA Intercontinental Cup title. * November 10 – 19: [[2017 FIBA Africa Women's Clubs Champions Cup]] in {{flagicon|ANG}} [[Luanda]]<ref>[http://www.fiba.basketball/womensafricachampionscup/2017/ FIBA's 2017 Africa Women's Clubs Champions Cup Page]</ref> ** {{flagicon|ANG}} [[C.D. Primeiro de Agosto (basketball)|Primeiro de Agosto]] defeated {{flagicon|MOZ}} Ferroviário de Maputo, 65–51, to win their third FIBA Africa Women's Clubs Champions Cup title. ** {{flagicon|NGR}} First Bank B.C. took third place. * December 11 – 20: [[2017 FIBA Africa Champions Cup]] in {{flagicon|TUN}} [[Radès]]<ref>[http://www.fiba.basketball/africachampionscup/2017 FIBA's 2017 Africa Clubs Champions Cup Page]</ref> ** {{flagicon|MAR}} [[AS Salé (Basketball)|AS Salé]] defeated {{flagicon|TUN}} [[Étoile Sportive de Radès (basketball)|Étoile Sportive de Radès]], 77–69, to win their first FIBA Africa Champions Cup title. ** {{flagicon|TUN}} Union Sportive Monastir took third place.
