{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}} {{Use British English|date=June 2015}} {{Infobox cricket ground | ground_name = J. Samuel White's Ground | nickname = | country = England | image = | location = [[Cowes]], [[Isle of Wight]] | establishment = 1953 | coord = {{coord|50.7572|-1.3121|display=inline}} | owner = [[Isle of Wight Council]] | seating_capacity = | end1 = | end2 = | year1 = 1956&ndash;1962 | club1 = [[Hampshire County Cricket Club|Hampshire]] | date = 30 December | year = 2011 | source = http://www.cricinfo.com/england/content/ground/56939.html Ground profile }}
'''J. Samuel White's Ground''' (also known as '''Plessey Ground''') is a sports ground in Park Road, [[Cowes]], [[Isle of Wight]], [[England]]. The ground is owned by the [[Isle of Wight Council]] and is surrounded by residential housing. A multitude of sports have been played at the ground, including [[cricket]], [[association football|football]] and [[bowls]].<ref name="HIST"/>
==History== The ground was originally owned by [[J. Samuel White|J. Samuel White & Co. Ltd.]], a ship builders based in Cowes. The company constructed the ground in 1953, with construction being funded by subscriptions from employees of the company.<ref name="PRO">{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/ground/56939.html|title=Ground profile: J. Samuel White's Ground|publisher=ESPNcricinfo|accessdate=30 December 2011}}</ref> [[Hampshire County Cricket Club|Hampshire]] first played [[first-class cricket]] there three years later in 1956, when [[Worcestershire County Cricket Club|Worcestershire]] were the visitors in the [[County Championship]],<ref name="FCM">{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/438_f.html|title=First-Class Matches played on J Samuel White's Ground, Cowes|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=30 December 2011}}</ref> with [[Colin Ingleby-Mackenzie]] scoring the maiden century on the ground in Hampshire's first-innings, followed by [[Laddy Outschoorn]] in Worcestershire's second-innings. The match ended in a draw.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/21/21985.html|title=Hampshire v Worcestershire, 1956 County Championship|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=30 December 2011}}</ref> Hampshire played a match there each year until 1962, playing seven first-class matches there.<ref name="FCM"/> However, J.Samuel White & Co. Ltd. fell on hard times, with the company's Cowes shipyard closing in 1963, bringing to an end Hampshire's use of the ground.<ref name="PRO"/> The ground was sought after for development, but planning was refused, with the ground falling into disuse.<ref name="PRO"/>
The ground was later bought in 1978 by the Isle of Wight Council. The council sought to offload the ground to a community-based organisation in 1984, with a lease being agreed with the Plessey Club.<ref name="HIST">{{cite web|url=http://www.iw-communityclub.co.uk/history.htm|title=History of IWCC|publisher=www.iw-communityclub.co.uk|accessdate=30 December 2011}}</ref> The Milne Memorial Sports Ground Co. Ltd was formed to acquire the lease and manage the day-to-day running of the club. When first acquired, the clubs membership was only open to employees and ex-employees of [[Plessey]]'s and J. Samuel White & Co.<ref name="HIST"/> Having been disused by until 1984, the cricket ground and football grounds had been used for hay making, the tennis courts and bowling greens were in a state of disrepair, as was the [[cricket pavilion|pavilion]]. The club borrowed £65,000 to extend the pavilion and £10,000 to building a new clubhouse for the bowling greens.<ref name="HIST"/> Hampshire returned there for a match in 1987 in aid of [[Malcolm Marshall]]'s benefit,<ref name="PRO"/> though the game didn't carry first-class or [[List A cricket|List A]] status. Today, the cricket ground is used by Cowes Cricket Club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cowes.play-cricket.com/home/home.asp|title=Cowes Cricket Club|publisher=www.cowes.play-cricket.com|accessdate=30 December 2011}}</ref> More recently, the club was able to acquire [[National Lottery (United Kingdom)|Lottery]] funding to the tune of £330,000 for an indoor bowls facility, though this was only possible by club members lending £100,000 themselves. The club is today open to membership for all residents of the Isle of Wight.<ref name="HIST"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iw-communityclub.co.uk/|title=Isle of Wight Community Club|publisher=www.iw-communityclub.co.uk|accessdate=30 December 2011}}</ref>
==Records==
===First-class=== * '''Highest team total:''' 398 by [[Glamorgan County Cricket Club|Glamorgan]] v [[Hampshire County Cricket Club|Hampshire]], 1960<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/24/24161.html|title=Hampshire v Glamorgan, 1960 County Championship|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=30 December 2011}}</ref> * '''Lowest team total:''' 84 by [[Leicestershire County Cricket Club|Leicestershire]] v Hampshire, 1958<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/438/f_Lowest_Team_Totals.html|title=J Samuel White's Ground, Cowes - Lowest Team Totals in first-class cricket|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=30 December 2011}}</ref> * '''Highest individual innings:''' 154[[not out|*]] by [[Laddy Outschoorn]] for [[Worcestershire County Cricket Club|Worcestershire]] v Hampshire, 1956<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/438/f_Centuries.html|title=J Samuel White's Ground, Cowes - Centuries in first-class cricket|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=30 December 2011}}</ref> * '''Best bowling in an innings:''' 7-81 by [[Derek Shackleton]] for Hampshire v [[Nottinghamshire County Cricket Club|Nottinghamshire]], 1957<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/438/f_Most_Wickets_in_Innings.html|title=J Samuel White's Ground, Cowes - Seven Wickets in an Innings in first-class cricket|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=30 December 2011}}</ref> * '''Best bowling in a match:''' 13-135 by Derek Shackleton, as above<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/438/f_Most_Wickets_in_Match.html|title=J Samuel White's Ground, Cowes - Most Wickets in a Match in first-class cricket|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=30 December 2011}}</ref>
